12/7/98

Trying to use assemble to improve cycle count for inport.

Some ideas:
  1. buffer refill check can be avoided if we can make sure there is enough
     data in buffer, for example for at least 1 macroblock.
  2. word boundary check can be avoid for VLD if we assume codeword is always
     less than 32 bits. (This, however, require some re-working of the inport
     and vld classes!)
  3. for fix-length fields that we know where the word boundary is, we can
     provide two version of getBit() and getBits(), one with and one without
     word boundary check.  (Limited usage for Video, but can be very useful
     for Systems bitstream.)
  4. Redefine inPort::bitPos to be compatible with csta.  Pass 32-nbits
     (i.e. cstb) instead of nbits as parameter in getBits().  The latter
     can be mapped with macro.

1. Info

MPEG-2 specifies the max #bits for a macroblock.  The worst case is slightly
larger than 1K bytes (Section 8.2).

MPEG-2 allows user to put private data in sequence, GOP and picture layers.
No user data is allowed at slice and MB layers.  Hence, it is possible to
bound the size of each segment of bitstream to read (MB and slice header).

Solution:
  - Add a funtion in BufferInfo to save rest of data and refill buffer.
    Data to be save: left over, last 4+ bytes, and possibly delay
    copied headers.
  - Before parsing slice header or macroblock data, check remaining
    data size and refill if necessary.
  - Have a version of getBit(s) and getByte(s) which do not check for
    buffer refill, and use them in slice and macroblock level parsing.

2. Considerations:
In general there are more shorter VLC than longer ones.

Current approach: always check for word boundary, but seldom read accross word.

New approach: never check for word boundary.  But need to refill 32-bit
              buffer before VLD.

 
